 seven or eight o'clock sometimes. 'Cos he had to go to Carn Brea station to put the mail bag - on the train. And we used to wait for the train come out and - sit in the little waiting room with a lovely fire there. Oh we used to think that was lovely to 
g
o up - if we were allowed out that was a special trip - to go up to the station. To go up with him that evening mother would go as well for a bit of walk you know. She didn't be - if she didn't have a busy day or anything like that she would - she'd - we'
d all go to the station.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971602 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14365183\charrsid12073373 Ten m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241735\charrsid12073373 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14365183\charrsid12073373 
nutes walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14353856 MP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14365183\charrsid12073373 That's right, yes.
